From a comparison of these passages with that in the text, itis plain that Bacon imagined the experiment to be successful, and that be had thereby proved the compressibility of water. The fact that the water exuded through the pores of the lead ought, however, to have shown him that the experiment was one which could not be relied upon.

‘This,¹ says Mr. Ellis, ‘is perhaps the most remarkable of Bacon¹s experiments; and it is singular that it was so little spoken of by sub· sequent writers. Nearly fifty years after the publication of the Novum Organum, an account of a similar experiment was published by Megalotti, who was secretary of the Accademia del Cimento at F lorence ; and it has
